5 A BILL
6 TO BE ENTITLED
7 AN ACT
8
9 Relating to 911 service; to add Section 11-98-4.3 to
10 the Code of Alabama 1975, to authorize the 911 Board to
11 institute a system to measure the emergency response
12 performance of local communication districts; to require, upon
13 request by the Attorney General, the 911 Board to audit local
14 communication districts and to submit a report on audit
15 findings to the Attorney General to be made public; and to
16 provide for a remediation plan by which to improve the
17 district's emergency response performance.
18 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
19 Section 1. Section 11-98-4.3 is added to the Code of
20 Alabama 1975, to read as follows:
21 §11-98-4.3
22 (a) For the purposes of this section, the term
23 "readiness" refers to the capability of a district, including
24 a public safety answering point, to expedite the answering,
25 receiving, and transferring of 911 calls and texts to
26 efficiently dispatch the appropriate emergency service
27 provider as soon as possible to a correct location where
28 property or life may be in jeopardy.
Page 1

property or life may be in jeopardy.
HB268 Engrossed
29 (b) The 911 Board shall establish a system that is
30 based upon best practices as adopted by nationally recognized
31 associations such as the National Emergency Number Association
32 and the Association of Public Safety Communications Officials
33 to measure the readiness of district public safety services
34 through the collection of data related to a district's
35 answering, receiving, transferring, and dispatching functions
36 relating to 911 calls, including voice, text messages, photos,
37 and videos.
38 (c) The 911 Board may collect data including, but not
39 limited to, all of the following for each district in the
40 state:
41 (1) 911 call volume.
42 (2) Time to answer 911 calls.
43 (3) Time to process emergency calls in accordance with
44 Section 11-98-11.
45 (4) Number of answered emergency calls versus
46 unanswered emergency calls.
47 (5) Number of dropped calls.
48 (6) Number of calls reporting a crime.
49 (d) Compliance by the 911 Board with this section may
50 be funded as an advisory service pursuant to Section
51 11-98-5.2(b)(7)b. or from any outside source of funding
52 received by the 911 Board.
53 (e)(1) The Attorney General, based upon a complaint
54 received concerning the performance of a local communication
55 district, may refer the matter to the 911 Board, which shall
56 conduct a performance audit to review and evaluate the
Page 2

conduct a performance audit to review and evaluate the
HB268 Engrossed
57 readiness of the district.
58 (2) A performance audit of a district by the 911 Board
59 may include any of the following:
60 a. Interviewing any individual who may have knowledge
61 concerning district performance, including members of the
62 district board of commissioners, the director of the PSAP,
63 public safety telecommunicators, heads of local emergency
64 service providers, first responders, and residents who have
65 submitted a complaint.
66 b. On-site inspection of a PSAP, PSAP equipment or
67 technical functionality, and monitoring PSAP operations in
68 real time.
69 (3)a. Upon completion of a performance audit or no
70 later than 60 days from commencement of the audit, the 911
71 Board shall approve and submit a formal written report to the
72 Attorney General which contains: (i) an evaluation of the
73 district's readiness; and (ii) findings of specific
74 operational deficiencies confirmed or disclosed by the audit.
75 b. If operational deficiencies are confirmed, the audit
76 report required under paragraph a. shall include a remediation
77 plan which prescribes measures to bring the district to an
78 acceptable level of readiness, including, but not limited to,
79 any of the following:
80 1. Training requirements for public safety
81 telecommunicators.
82 2. Hiring additional public safety telecommunicators.
83 3. Upgrade of technology, including replacement or
84 acquisition of PSAP communications hardware or software.
Page 3

acquisition of PSAP communications hardware or software.
HB268 Engrossed
85 4. Amendment of PSAP operating protocols, scripts, and
86 recordkeeping.
87 c. The audit report shall be made public and may be
88 posted on the website of the Attorney General or the 911
89 Board.
90 (4) Pursuant to the performance audit, the 911 Board is
91 authorized to supervise the implementation of a remediation
92 plan in the district.
93 (f) The 911 Board shall adopt rules in accordance with
94 the Alabama Administrative Procedure Act which are necessary
95 to implement the system described in this section.
96 Section 2. This act shall become effective on October
97 1, 2026.
